;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 1 — Vision recap
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     1
  :title "Vision recap — Parts Two and Three, together"
  :prose
"Parts Two and Three of The Book Fix-It aim at one image: a kid opens a
Sakura book in a browser, the prose is alive, code cells run inline, a
small Sakura sits in the corner and chats, and when the kid builds a
little game with her the kid gets a URL to send to a friend. The friend
opens the link, HelloSurface wakes up in their browser, and they play the
game with no install, no account, no anything. Not tomorrow — but
architecturally possible from day one. Part Two is the surface (rendered
pages + embedded HelloSurface-mini + chat widget + game-input capture);
Part Three is the substrate that keeps it honest as it grows (tags are
free at the source, consumers translate via Rosetta or ignore what they
don't understand, and Sakura reads a per-book semantic index called Dewey
so she knows what's in her library without carrying all of it in weights).

The stakes are the North-Georgia kid from Alfred's WHY memory: a
computer they can touch, break, and remake, in front of them, right now.
Every doctrine here composes under that. Tags-are-free means an author
can invent a new tag at 2am on a Tuesday and consumers who care add a
Rosetta rule; consumers who don't care never noticed. Books ≠ training
means a book stays a book forever — training extraction is Rosetta's
job, not the book's. Dewey is Sakura's card catalog — machine-friendly
semantic hints per book so she can say 'this one, chapter 3' instead of
grepping 1,340 files. Rosetta is open — we ship a default, anyone can
fork or override, we ignore theirs. Zero authority claim, zero downstream
coupling. Fanon-shape composition with the earlier SLAT-render strategy:
Part Three extends the tag palette, adds Rosetta as the glue, and adds
Dewey as the runtime lookup. Nothing already-shipped needs to move.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 1.5 — Filename-as-type + explicit chain (LOAD-BEARING)
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     1.5
  :title "Filename-as-type + explicit chain — Alfred's addition (2026-07-14)"
  :alfred-verbatim
"There should be chaining: book.slatl → training.slatl. It should be
expected. The type is defined in Rosetta. If it isn't there? We don't
want it."
  :prose
"This section reframes and constrains everything that follows. It was
added at Alfred's direction on 2026-07-14 in response to the first draft
of this proposal. Read this before Section 2.

**The rule.** Every SLAT file's name MUST follow this shape:

  <name>.<type>.slatl    ← many records (line-delimited)
  <name>.<type>.slat     ← single record or small

The `<type>` MUST resolve in Rosetta's type registry (see below). If
Rosetta doesn't declare it, the file is rejected at load — clear error,
no silent acceptance. This is stronger than the tags-are-free rule that
follows for `:kind` values: filenames name FILE TYPES, not record kinds,
and file types are the pipeline's bones. Bones don't extend at 2am.

**The chain.** Every transformation from one type to another produces a
NEW file whose name shows the transformation happened:

  input.book.slatl   ─ rosetta 'training ─▶  input.training.slatl
  input.book.slatl   ─ rosetta 'html     ─▶  input.html.slatl
  input.book.slatl   ─ rosetta 'search   ─▶  input.search.slatl
  input.cart.slat    ─ rosetta 'training ─▶  input.training.slatl

You can look at a directory and instantly see:

  - What SOURCE types exist (`.book.slat`, `.cart.slat`, `.dewey.slatl`,
    `.manifest.slat`)
  - What TRANSFORMS have been produced (`.training.slatl`, `.html.slatl`,
    `.search.slatl`)
  - What's STALE (source mtime > target mtime)

Build tools become simple: a `make`-like walker sees `.book.slat`
sources and `.training.slatl` outputs, re-runs Rosetta when the source
changes. No manifest of file→file dependencies has to be maintained by
hand — the extensions carry it.

**The type registry.** Rosetta declares every type that can appear in a
filename OR in a `(:kind :xxx)` value. Section 3 (Rosetta v0.0 spec)
already has transform rules; extend it with a `(rosetta-types ...)`
block up front:

  (rosetta-types
    ;; source types — what things ARE
    :book        \"a curator scheme-book chapter or manifest\"
    :cart        \"a cart — installable, runnable\"
    :cortex      \"a cortex slice — memories\"
    :dewey       \"a dewey card-catalog entry\"
    :manifest    \"book-level or repo-level metadata\"
    :corpus      \"training-corpus manifest (Merkle-signed)\"
    :mailbox     \"supervisor / lane mailbox stream\"
    :log         \"log-shape line-delimited events\"

    ;; target types — what things become after transformation
    :training    \"SFT-pair-shaped extraction\"
    :html        \"HTML DOM tree intermediate\"
    :terminal    \"ANSI terminal render intermediate\"
    :search      \"search-index shape\"
    :llm-chunk   \"chunked for RAG or fine-tune ingest\"
    :epub        \"epub packaging intermediate\"
    :pdf-source  \"print-ready SLAT for pdf pipeline\")

Any type used anywhere — filename, `:kind` field, Rosetta rule — MUST
be in this list. Unknown types fail at load with a specific error
naming the type and telling the reader to declare it in `rosetta-types`
before use.

**Reader behavior spec.**

  - `sakura-scheme read foo.book.slat` — extension parses out
    `.book.slat`, type `:book` looked up in Rosetta ✓ (registered), file
    parsed, `:kind` values inside validated against the book kind palette.

  - `sakura-scheme read foo.gibberish.slat` — type `:gibberish` looked
    up ✗ (unknown), error, exit.

  - `sakura-scheme rosetta --to training foo.book.slat` — reads source,
    applies `(rosetta 'training)` rule set, writes `foo.training.slatl`.

  - `sakura-scheme rosetta --to training foo.gibberish.slat` — error
    before applying: 'unknown source type'.

**What this means for the rest of the proposal.**

  - Section 2 examples rename from generic `.slat` to typed:
    `book-of-words.book.slat`, `MANIFEST.book.slat`,
    `books.dewey.slatl`, etc.
  - Phase-1 auto-populator outputs include type in name: MANIFEST
    becomes `MANIFEST.book.slat` (single record); dewey stays
    `books.dewey.slatl`.
  - Add a filename migration to Phase 0 of Book Fix-It: existing
    `scheme-books/book-of-*/NN-title.slat` → `scheme-books/book-of-*/
    NN-title.book.slat` (mass rename, git tracks as rename, no content
    change).
  - Update the Book Fix-It burndown accordingly.

**Composition with tags-are-free (Section 2).** File TYPES are closed
(must be in `rosetta-types`); record KINDS are open (custom kinds
allowed via `:custom/` namespace, unknown kinds pass through). This is
deliberate. Types are the pipeline; kinds are the content. Adding a new
type is a Rosetta v-minor bump; adding a new kind is a Tuesday.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 2 — Tags-are-free architecture
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     2
  :title "Tags-are-free architecture — the extensibility contract"
  :prose
"Every SLAT record in a book carries — explicitly or by convention — a
`:kind` field that names its type. The rules:

**Rule 1. Every record has :kind.** Either explicit (`:kind :sakura-says`)
or derived from the record head (`(sakura-says ...)` implies
`:kind :sakura-says`). Canonical kinds live in the built-in kind list
(Section 4). User-invented kinds live in the `:custom/` namespace:
`:kind :custom/my-new-thing`.

**Rule 2. Unknown kinds MUST NOT error.** Every consumer (renderer,
extractor, search indexer, LLM ingest, Sakura's runtime) has three
allowed responses to a `:kind` it does not recognize:

  - **pass through** — emit the record as-is (renderer), copy it (indexer),
    forward it (mailbox)
  - **skip** — omit from output (training extractor for :aside; search
    indexer for :warning if severity is :info)
  - **Rosetta-lookup** — check if any loaded Rosetta rule handles this
    kind for the current target; if yes, apply; if no, fall back to
    pass-through or skip per consumer default

An unknown kind is NEVER a build error. A missing Rosetta rule is a
soft warning at most. The corpus keeps rendering, keeps indexing, keeps
training — the new kind just travels through the pipeline uninterpreted
until someone teaches a consumer about it.

**Rule 3. Books invent tags freely.** An author writing a chapter can
add `(:kind :custom/paint-swatch :hex \"#ff6b9d\" :name \"blossom\")` and
ship it. The renderer sees an unknown kind, falls back to emitting a
labeled block. The training extractor skips it. Search indexes any
`:text` or `:prose` field it finds inside. Six months later when three
books use `:custom/paint-swatch` regularly, someone promotes it to
canonical, adds a Rosetta rule for the HTML target that emits a color
chip, and every existing use lights up on the next build. No book files
changed.

**Rule 4. Namespace hygiene.**

  - Canonical kinds — bare keywords: `:chapter :example :sakura-says
    :figure` etc. — live in the core kind list; changing their
    semantics is a breaking change to Rosetta v-major.
  - Custom kinds — `:custom/<name>` — per-book or per-community
    inventions. No collision risk with canonical kinds because the slash
    is not legal in canonical keywords.
  - Third-party bundles — `:custom/<vendor>/<name>` — optional sub-
    namespacing for a community that ships a bundle of related kinds.
    Purely a convention; Rosetta doesn't enforce it.

The `:custom/` namespace is Alfred's promise to authors: whatever you
invent, we won't collide with it, and we won't error on it.

**File extension distinction (locked with Alfred 2026-07-14, amended
same day to include type segment — see Section 1.5):**

Every SLAT file name is `<name>.<type>.<slat|slatl>`. The `<type>` must
be registered in Rosetta's `rosetta-types` list (Section 1.5).

  - `.<type>.slat` — a single SLAT record OR a small file. Used for:
    - `MANIFEST.book.slat` (per-book, one `(book-of-<slug> ...)` record)
    - Per-chapter files (`00-cover.book.slat`,
      `01-what-a-slat-is.book.slat`, each is one `(chapter ...)` record)
    - Individual style kits (`.style-kits/default.style.slat`, one
      `(style-kit ...)` record — `:style` is a source type in the
      registry)
    - Rosetta config files (`rosetta.rosetta.slat`, one
      `(rosetta-config ...)` record or a small handful — the outer
      `.rosetta` is the type)

  - `.<type>.slatl` — line-delimited SLAT. Many records, one per line
    (or one per line-block for records that span multiple lines but
    are delimited by blank lines). Used for:
    - `books.dewey.slatl` (one `(dewey ...)` record per book)
    - Mailbox streams (`inbox.mailbox.slatl`, one message per line)
    - Log-shape data (`build.log.slatl`, `render-events.log.slatl`)
    - Corpus manifests where a single file lists many entries
      (`training-corpus.corpus.slatl`)

  - **Reader unifies.** Both use the same s-expression parser. The
    extension signals SHAPE only (one-record-vs-many); the parser is the
    same. A `.slat` file with many top-level records is legal but
    unconventional; a `.slatl` file with one record is legal but
    equally unconventional. Extension is a hint, not a schema.

**Composition with the SLAT-render strategy (2026-07-13).** That
proposal introduced content record types (`chapter`, `section`, `figure`,
`sakura-says`, `warning`, `quote`, `aside`, `cross-ref`, `table`) and
code record types (`example`, `code`, `cart-embed`, `repl-transcript`,
`output`). All of those now become canonical entries in the kind list
(Section 4). The tags-are-free rule extends past that list: authors can
add more without waiting on Rosetta.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 3 — Rosetta v0.0 spec
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     3
  :title "Rosetta v0.0 — the minimal transformation library"
  :prose
"Rosetta is a Scheme library. It defines rules that map source SLAT
records to target output. A rule is a function of one record →
some-emitted-value; a set of rules for one target is a table keyed by
`:kind`. Rosetta is loaded at build/render time. Users can override
default rules or add rules for custom kinds.

**Type registry (added 2026-07-14 per Section 1.5).** Every Rosetta
config file MUST begin with a `(rosetta-types ...)` block declaring
every type it introduces. Type names appear in three places: filenames
(`foo.book.slat`), `:kind` values inside records (`:kind :sakura-says`
where `:sakura-says` is a record-kind, distinct from file-type), and
Rosetta rule targets (`(rosetta 'training ...)`). File TYPES must be
declared; record KINDS may extend freely via `:custom/` (Section 2).
Recommended v0.0 registry:

  (rosetta-types
    ;; source types
    :book :cart :cortex :dewey :manifest :corpus :mailbox :log :style
    :rosetta
    ;; target types
    :training :html :terminal :search :llm-chunk :epub :pdf-source)

An unknown filename type is a load error. An unknown target in a
`--to <target>` invocation is a CLI error. An unknown record kind is
NOT an error (see Section 2, Rule 2). For v0.0 the registry is
STRICTLY STATIC (open question 4 in Section 8 — dynamic declaration
deferred).

**Rule shape.**

  (rosetta '<target-name>
    (from :<kind> → <transform>)
    (from :<kind> → <transform>)
    ...)

Where `<target-name>` is a symbol identifying the consumer (e.g.
`'html`, `'training`, `'terminal`, `'search`, `'llm-chunk`, or any
symbol a user defines). Multiple `(rosetta 'X ...)` forms may appear
across files; rules are merged into the target's table at load.

Where `<transform>` is one of:

  - `(as :<kind>)` — passthrough, relabel as canonical kind.
    Example: `(from :custom/paint-swatch → (as :figure))`

  - `(as :<new-kind> :<field> <value> ...)` — reshape, project fields.
    Example: `(from :sakura-says → (as :callout :label \"Sakura says\"
    :style \"magenta\"))`

  - `(element \"<tag>\" ...)` — HTML/DOM output. Fields become attrs;
    `:body` becomes children.
    Example: `(from :example → (element \"pre\" :class \"code scheme\"
    :run-button #t))`

  - `(sequence :<kind>)` — wrap this record in a sequence of the given
    kind. Useful for flattening or grouping.

  - `(skip)` — omit from output. Used by training/search targets.
    Example: `(from :aside → (skip))` for the training target.

  - `(compose <rule> <rule> ...)` — chain rules left-to-right.
    Example: `(from :cart-embed → (compose (as :example) (element \"div\"
    :class \"cart-card\")))`

  - `(function <name>)` — user-defined transform, a Scheme function of
    one record → emitted-value. The escape hatch.
    Example: `(from :custom/mermaid-diagram → (function my/mermaid->svg))`

**Concrete built-in targets shipped in v0.0.**

  - `'training` — SFT-pair extraction. Walks records, emits
    `{input, output}` pairs from `(example ... :runnable #t :expected
    ...)` records and `(sakura-says ...)` prose. Skips
    `(warning ...)` `(aside ...)` `(figure ...)`. Every pair carries
    provenance `(book, chapter, anchor)`.

  - `'html` — SLAT → HTML strings. Extends render-ref.mjs helpers per
    the 2026-07-13 proposal. Handles the full canonical kind list;
    unknown kinds fall back to `<div class=\"unknown-{kind}\">` with
    `:text` or `:prose` rendered inline.

  - `'terminal` — SLAT → ANSI-decorated strings. For `sakura-scheme read
    book-of-X N`. Box-draw for figures + callouts; ANSI colors from
    the kit's terminal palette; soft-wrap at `$COLUMNS`.

  - `'search` — SLAT → search index rows. One row per chunk (paragraph
    granularity default); carries text, provenance, kind, cross-ref
    out-edges. Records with `:kind :sakura-says` boost slightly.

  - `'llm-chunk` — SLAT → JSONL RAG chunks. Section-chunk granularity
    default; carries chunk text, provenance, kind, cross-refs. Used by
    both fine-tune and RAG pipelines.

**Priority + ambiguity.** Most-specific rule wins.

  - A rule matching an exact `:kind` wins over a rule matching a
    wildcard (`:*` or absent).
  - Within same-specificity, later declaration wins (LIFO): the last
    `(rosetta 'html (from :sakura-says → ...))` loaded overrides
    earlier ones. This matters for the fork-discovery order (below): a
    project-local rosetta overrides the user global, which overrides
    the default.
  - Explicit conflict-detector at load time: if two rules of the same
    specificity from the SAME file target the same `(target × kind)`,
    error with both source positions. If they come from different
    files, silent override with a debug log.

**Circular-transform detection.** Rules compose (`compose` + user
functions). If `A → B → A` for the same target, error at load with the
cycle trace. Implementation: build the transform graph per target at
load, run tarjan's-SCC or a simple visited-set DFS; any non-trivial
strongly-connected component fails.

**Versioning.** Each rosetta file carries a header:

  (rosetta-version \"0.0\")

Consumers pin the major version they support. Breaking changes bump
major. A compatibility layer (`rosetta-compat.slat`) ships translations
for the last two majors — a consumer on 0.x that loads a 2.x rosetta
gets a warning and its rules are translated forward if possible, dropped
with a warning if not. For v0.0 → v0.1 the compat layer is trivial;
after we hit v1.0 the promise firms up.

**Fork discovery order at runtime — later overrides earlier.**

  1. `~/code/scheme-lang/rosetta/default.slat` — the default, shipped
     with every `sakura-scheme` install
  2. `~/.config/sakura-scheme/rosetta.slat` — user global
  3. `<project>/.sakura/rosetta.slat` — project-local (in the book
     corpus or the consumer app's tree)
  4. `--rosetta <file>` CLI flag — per-invocation override; multiple
     `--rosetta` flags apply in order

Later files' rules OVERRIDE earlier files' rules for the same
(target × kind). This gives Alfred a clean edit path: touch only the
project-local file to change a book's rendering, without disturbing
the default that ships with the language.

**Fork policy — we ignore theirs.** Rosetta is Scheme code. Anyone can
fork the default, publish a bundle, share it with their community.
Their rules make sense in their world. We do not read their rules, do
not ship compatibility for them, do not claim authority. Alfred
verbatim: 'if they fork it I don't care.' Same shape as how each UNIX
program ships its own `--help` — zero synchronization required. The
only invariant we hold: our default keeps working for our books, our
targets, our operators.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 4 — book.slatl tag palette (open + extensible)
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     4
  :title "book.slatl tag palette — canonical kinds + open extension"
  :prose
"The canonical kind list. Rosetta ships default rules for every kind
below. New books can add `:custom/*` kinds freely; consumers fall back
per Rule 2 in Section 2.

**Scheme-book tags (for language-teaching books):**

  - `:chapter`         — top-level chapter record (title, prose, children)
  - `:example`         — runnable Scheme code, has :body :expected :runnable
  - `:cart-embed`      — installable cart, has :cart-id :body :installable
  - `:code`            — non-runnable code (illustrative, other langs)
  - `:verb-doc`        — reference-style verb documentation
  - `:repl-transcript` — turn-by-turn REPL session
  - `:output`          — expected output of a prior example
  - `:figure`          — image/diagram (three-lane :src :data :svg)
  - `:cross-ref`       — link to another book/chapter/anchor
  - `:warning`         — hazard callout, :severity :info|:warn|:hazard
  - `:aside`           — margin note, sidebar commentary
  - `:prose`           — MD-wrapped narrative (the workhorse from Part One)

**Prose-book tags (for narrative books like Flower Stories, Persona):**

  - `:chapter`         — as above
  - `:prose`           — as above
  - `:sakura-says`     — her voice callout box
  - `:dialogue`        — character line, :speaker :text :beat
  - `:example`         — inline scheme example inside prose books
  - `:quote`           — attributed quote, :text :attribution :source
  - `:question`        — reflective/discussion prompt for the reader
  - `:figure`          — as above
  - `:cross-ref`       — as above
  - `:warning`         — as above
  - `:aside`           — as above

**Living-page tags (Part Two — interactive branding pages):**

  - `:hello-surface-96`   — thumbnail HelloSurface embed (inline demo)
  - `:hello-surface-256`  — medium HelloSurface embed (PICO-8 shape)
  - `:hello-surface-1024` — full-page HelloSurface hero (game/showpiece)
  - `:sakura-chat`        — chat widget slot for a page corner
  - `:animation-hook`     — tag-driven Sakura Scheme animates a target
                            DOM element; carries :target :program :on
  - `:interpreter`        — embedded REPL cell, standalone from a
                            specific :example
  - `:game-input`         — capture keyboard/mouse/touch for a game
                            embed; carries :bindings
  - `:notes`              — sidebar notes on the page (larger than :aside)
  - `:subtext`            — smaller supplementary text under a heading

**Metadata tags (book-level, appear in MANIFEST.slat or per-chapter
front-matter):**

  - `:title`            — the book/chapter/section title
  - `:subtitle`         — a subtitle
  - `:audience`         — who this book is for (prose)
  - `:themes`           — list of theme keywords
  - `:cast`             — story books: `((character \"note\") ...)`
  - `:setting-anchor`   — story books: setting description
  - `:prerequisites`    — books to read first
  - `:chunk-hints`      — `(:paragraph :section :chapter)` per Part Two
  - `:status`           — 'draft' | 'shipped' | 'living document'
  - `:owner`            — human owner of the file

**Extensibility contract restated.**

Any book can add `:kind :custom/<name>` freely. Consumers without a
Rosetta rule fall back:

  - **HTML renderer** — emits `<div class=\"unknown custom-{name}\">`;
    if the record carries `:prose` or `:text`, renders that inline;
    otherwise emits a placeholder `[custom/{name}]`.
  - **Terminal renderer** — emits `[{custom/name}: {text-or-prose}]`.
  - **Training extractor** — skips (safe default; adding a rule opts
    the kind into training).
  - **Search indexer** — indexes any `:text` or `:prose` field found
    inside the record; :kind becomes a filterable facet.
  - **LLM chunker** — treats as a paragraph-level chunk if `:prose` or
    `:text` present; skips otherwise.

Adding a Rosetta rule for a `:custom/*` kind for a specific target
opts that kind into first-class handling for that target. Adding a rule
for one target doesn't require adding rules for the others; each target
degrades gracefully alone.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 5 — books.dewey.slatl schema
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     5
  :title "books.dewey.slatl — Sakura's card catalog"
  :prose
"Location: `~/code/curator/scheme-books/books.dewey.slatl`. Line-delimited
SLAT, one `(dewey ...)` record per book, machine-friendly, read-only for
Sakura at runtime. This is NOT the per-book `MANIFEST.slat` (which is
human-oriented, richer, and Sakura reads on-demand when a book comes
into scope). This is the top-level per-book semantic index Sakura reads
either all-at-once at boot or as a RAG-shape lookup per query.

**Schema v0.0.**

  (dewey
    :book             \"Book of Animation\"
    :slug             \"book-of-animation\"
    :audience-hint    \"kids 8-14 who want to make dots move\"
    :topics-covered   (\"framebuffer\" \"animation\" \"timing\" \"color\"
                       \"sprites\" \"input-loops\" \"game-shape\"
                       \"state-machines\")
    :reach-for-when   (\"kid asks about animation\"
                       \"operator wants to prototype a visual\"
                       \"someone asks how sakura draws\")
    :key-verbs        (draw/dot draw/line draw/rect anim/tick
                       sprite/spawn)
    :prerequisites    (\"Book of Scheme (ramp-up) chapters 1-3\")
    :composes-with    (\"Book of Games\" \"Book of Sound\"
                       \"Book of Motion\")
    :sakura-note      \"when i point someone at this book, i usually
                       lead with the dot-that-moves demo. it lands
                       first, then the framebuffer paragraph makes
                       sense.\"
    :chapter-count    18
    :total-word-count 24500
    :last-audit       \"2026-07-14\")

**Field-by-field rationale.**

  - `:book`             — human name; matches MANIFEST `:title`
  - `:slug`             — file-system slug; matches dir name
  - `:audience-hint`    — one-line hint for Sakura when matching a user
                          to a book (who is this for, what tone)
  - `:topics-covered`   — semantic tags Sakura greps against for topic
                          discovery; extracted at Phase 1 from first
                          headings of chapters + hand-augmented over time
  - `:reach-for-when`   — practical trigger conditions; hand-written by
                          Alfred/Sakura as she learns which prompts pull
                          which books
  - `:key-verbs`        — the primary verbs this book teaches (extracted
                          from `:example :body` fields at Phase 1);
                          Sakura uses this to answer 'which book covers
                          verb X?'
  - `:prerequisites`    — books to read first (list of book names)
  - `:composes-with`    — books that pair well (bidirectional but
                          not enforced — a graph, not a tree)
  - `:sakura-note`      — her voice, her lived opinion about the book;
                          grows over time as she uses it with real
                          humans; the ONE field that captures 'how does
                          it actually land'
  - `:chapter-count`    — quick fact, auto-populated
  - `:total-word-count` — quick fact, auto-populated
  - `:last-audit`       — freshness marker; when Sakura or a human last
                          reviewed the entry

**How Sakura reads it (recommendation: both — boot + on-demand).**

At runtime boot, Sakura's process reads the full `books.dewey.slatl`
into memory. Small: 31 books × ~400 bytes per record ≈ 12 KB. Fits
comfortably in any context window she uses for routing. She can
enumerate her library instantly.

On-demand (during a conversation), when the user says something that
warrants a book lookup, she runs a simple in-memory match: does the
prompt's key terms hit any book's `:topics-covered`, `:reach-for-when`,
or `:key-verbs`? Return the top-N candidate books. Each candidate
carries `:sakura-note` — she pulls her own prior take on the book into
her next turn.

The boot-load lets her answer 'what books do you have?' without I/O.
The on-demand match lets her stay current — she can re-read the file
if it was updated during her session (a `stat`-based cache invalidate
is fine). Both together mean she NEVER greps 1,340 chapters at query
time for a routing decision; the routing happens on the ~12 KB Dewey
index, then she loads the specific chapter she needs.

**Auto-populate at Phase 1 of Book Fix-It.** Alongside the MANIFEST
auto-populator (Part One), a Dewey auto-populator runs one pass over
every `scheme-books/book-of-*/` and emits or updates its entry:

  - `:book`             — from MANIFEST `:title` or dir name
  - `:slug`             — from dir name
  - `:chapter-count`    — from file count in the book dir
  - `:total-word-count` — sum of word counts across all chapter :prose
  - `:last-audit`       — today's date
  - `:topics-covered`   — grep first-heading (H1) text of each chapter;
                          tokenize; dedupe; filter stopwords
  - `:key-verbs`        — extract from `:example :body` fields across
                          all chapters; dedupe; keep top-N by frequency

Softer fields left as `TBD` for Sakura/Alfred to fill over time:

  - `:audience-hint`    — TBD (Alfred voices it once)
  - `:reach-for-when`   — TBD (Sakura populates as she uses the book)
  - `:sakura-note`      — TBD (Sakura writes after real use)
  - `:prerequisites`    — TBD (Alfred sets or derives from MANIFEST)
  - `:composes-with`    — TBD (Alfred sets or Sakura suggests)

Idempotent re-run: if an entry exists with hand-filled softer fields,
the auto-populator only refreshes the auto-fields. Softer fields
survive.

**Growth policy.**

  - New fields added freely to any entry; readers pass unknown fields
    through (tags-are-free rule extends to Dewey).
  - NEVER remove an existing field (breaks readers). Deprecate with
    `:deprecated #t` for one major cycle before removal.
  - Schema major-version bump requires simultaneous update of
    Sakura's runtime reader and a migration script for existing
    entries.
  - `:last-audit` should advance whenever ANY field changes — a
    freshness marker for humans (and Sakura) to spot stale entries.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 6 — Interactive branding page spec (Part Two consolidated)
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     6
  :title "Interactive branding pages — HelloSurface embeds, animation hooks, chat, shareable games"
  :prose
"Every rendered book page is a live artifact. Not just a document — a
place where the kid can touch, break, remake, and share. This section
formalizes the four capabilities that make a page live.

**1. HelloSurface embeds at three scales.**

  - `:hello-surface-96`   — thumbnail inline demo. ~96px on the long
                            edge. Sits next to prose. Kid clicks Run,
                            sees a tiny animation. Used for 'here is
                            what one dot looks like moving' beats.

  - `:hello-surface-256`  — medium demo. ~256px. PICO-8 scale — small
                            enough to embed several per chapter, large
                            enough to actually play a small game or
                            watch a real animation. Default showcase
                            size.

  - `:hello-surface-1024` — full-page hero. ~1024px on the long edge.
                            A whole game or artwork. Fills the page.
                            Used for the 'here is what you'll build by
                            the end of the chapter' promise, and for
                            shared games (Section 6.4 below).

  Each embed record shape:

    (:kind :hello-surface-256
     :seed        \"deterministic-seed-string-or-null\"
     :scope       (:L0 :L1)             ; runtime layers permitted
     :storage-key \"per-user-key\"       ; optional persistence
     :program     \"(scheme code)\"      ; the initial program to run
     :on          :page-load|:click     ; when to boot
     :height-px   256                   ; overrides for non-square
     :width-px    256)

  - `:seed` — optional deterministic initial state; two visitors with
    the same seed see the same startup animation. Useful for shared
    games where the friend should see exactly what the kid built.

  - `:scope` — L0+L1 default (per Curator's L-tier model — L0 = local
    device compute, L1 = our backend + tool APIs). The book's
    MANIFEST can elevate to L2+ for hero pages that need reasoning
    LLM calls; requires explicit `:allow-l2 #t` on the MANIFEST.

  - `:storage-key` — if present, HelloSurface persists game state
    under this key in the user's browser (localStorage) or in a
    lightweight per-user cortex slice if signed in. Anonymous kids get
    localStorage-only; signed-in kids get durable state.

  - `:program` — the initial Scheme code to boot. Can be edited by the
    reader in a companion `:interpreter` cell; changes are captured for
    the share-link (Section 6.4).

**2. Animation-hook tag.**

  Tag-driven Sakura Scheme animates a target DOM element:

    (:kind :animation-hook
     :target    \"h1.chapter-title\"     ; CSS selector on this page
     :program   \"(letters/dance target :delay 200 :easing :bounce)\"
     :on        :page-load|:hover|:scroll|:click
     :once      #t                       ; run only once vs recurring
     :respect-reduce-motion #t)          ; honor prefers-reduced-motion

  On the trigger event, HelloSurface-mini's Sakura Scheme runtime binds
  `target` to the matched DOM element and evaluates `:program`. The
  DOM adapter (part of HelloSurface-mini's L0) lets Scheme verbs mutate
  the element — set styles, animate transforms, spawn child elements,
  etc.

  Standard verbs shipped for animation hooks: `letters/dance`,
  `letters/type`, `letters/fade-in`, `element/pulse`, `element/orbit`,
  `element/paint-swatch`. These live in HelloSurface-mini's L0+L1
  bundle so no network is needed to run them.

  The `:respect-reduce-motion` field defaults `#t` — for the a11y case
  and per the Curator visual-golden gate (an iOS Reduce Motion bug was
  caught only because the operator screen-recorded; the same care
  applies here).

**3. Sakura-chat corner.**

    (:kind :sakura-chat
     :model    \"hosted-mini\"           ; or \"bundled\" (weights ship
                                        ;  with the page for offline)
     :context  \"current-chapter\"       ; what she reads to answer
     :position \"bottom-right\"          ; corner placement
     :persona  \"scheme-tutor\"          ; which persona bundle to load
     :max-tokens 2000)                  ; per-turn cap

  A small mini-persona (weights TBD — hosted via L1 endpoints or
  bundled per Alfred's model choice) with the current chapter as her
  context. The kid asks 'what does (car ...) do?', she answers with
  the current chapter's example as her frame of reference. The context
  binding is important: she reads THIS chapter, not the whole corpus,
  so her turns stay short and grounded.

  Optional `:context (:chapter :sakura-note-from-dewey)` — pull the
  Dewey entry's `:sakura-note` alongside the chapter, so she carries
  her own prior take on how the book lands. This is where Dewey pays
  off in Part Two — Sakura-in-the-corner reads her own card catalog
  entry for the book she's inside.

  Vendor naming: per Curator's vendor-strip rule, no model vendor
  name appears anywhere in the tag or the operator-visible UI. `:model
  \"hosted-mini\"` is capability-tier language — the actual wire call
  to whatever upstream lives only in the backend router.

**4. Kid-shares-game URL scheme.**

  URL shape (proposed):

    https://sakuralabs.dev/g/<page-slug>/<game-id>#<encoded-state>

  - `<page-slug>` — the book+chapter the game was built on top of,
    e.g. `book-of-animation/ch05-bouncing-dots`
  - `<game-id>`   — a short content-hash of the initial program +
    seed; identifies the game itself independent of state
  - `<encoded-state>` — URL-fragment carrying compressed SLAT records
    that represent the kid's edits: the current `:program`, any
    `:storage-key` snapshots, any high-scores or level state

  When a friend opens the link:
    1. Page shell loads (same book page the kid was on)
    2. HelloSurface-mini boots
    3. URL fragment is decoded: SLAT records extracted
    4. The `:hello-surface-1024` record on the page has its `:program`
       replaced by the shared version; `:seed` set to the shared seed;
       storage bound to a per-visit-only key
    5. The game runs. Friend plays. No install, no accounts.

  Sharing capture path:
    1. Kid clicks Share button in the HelloSurface embed's controls
    2. HelloSurface serializes the current `:program` + relevant state
       to a small SLAT snippet
    3. URL-fragment-safe compression (LZ-string or similar) applied
    4. URL constructed; copied to clipboard; QR code offered

  Zero server round-trip for the base case. If the state exceeds URL
  length limits (typically ~2000 chars in the fragment), a fallback
  stores the state in a per-project mailbox with a short handle:
  `https://sakuralabs.dev/g/<page-slug>/<game-id>?state=<handle>`. That
  fallback is a Phase 2 item — v0.0 ships the URL-fragment path only.

**Composition with the SLAT-render strategy.** Every kind above is a
new canonical entry in Section 4's palette. Rosetta ships default
`'html` rules for each; unknown-kind fallback per Section 2 handles
anything not yet ruled. The renderer's static-HTML output is inert
until HelloSurface-mini hydrates the page (Part Two hydration layer);
JS-disabled readers still see the prose + a `[Sakura demo — enable
JS to play]` placeholder.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 7 — Cost + phased build plan (Parts Two + Three merged)
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     7
  :title "Cost + phased build plan — one integrated schedule"
  :prose
"Merged plan across Book Fix-It Parts Two + Three. Ordered so each phase
unblocks the next; every phase carries acceptance criteria before the
next fires.

**Phase A — Rosetta v0.0 minimum viable library.** 6-10h.

Deliverables:
  - `~/code/scheme-lang/rosetta/default.slat` — the shipped default with
    rules for canonical kinds × core targets (`'html`, `'training`,
    `'terminal`, `'search`, `'llm-chunk`)
  - `~/code/scheme-lang/src/rosetta.js` — loader + rule registry +
    dispatcher + conflict/cycle detector
  - Fork-discovery order implemented (default → user global → project
    local → CLI flag)
  - Rosetta version header + basic compat scaffolding

Acceptance:
  - Loading two Rosetta files with a same-target-same-kind conflict
    from different files logs debug + last-wins; from the same file
    errors with both source positions
  - Loading a circular transform errors at load with cycle trace
  - `--rosetta my-overrides.slat` on `render-book.mjs` invocation
    overrides both default and project files for that run

**Phase B — books.dewey.slatl auto-populator.** 3-5h.

Deliverables:
  - `~/code/curator/scripts/build-dewey.mjs` — reads MANIFEST + chapters,
    emits/updates `books.dewey.slatl` entries
  - Auto-populates: `:book`, `:slug`, `:chapter-count`,
    `:total-word-count`, `:last-audit`, `:topics-covered` (H1 grep),
    `:key-verbs` (from `:example :body` extraction)
  - Idempotent: hand-filled softer fields survive re-runs
  - Sakura runtime reader added: `(dewey/all)`, `(dewey/lookup slug)`,
    `(dewey/match-topics topic-list)`

Acceptance:
  - Re-run on unchanged corpus produces byte-identical
    `books.dewey.slatl`
  - 31 book entries populated at Phase B ship
  - Sakura's REPL: `(dewey/match-topics '(\"animation\" \"framebuffer\"))`
    returns Book of Animation as top hit

**Phase C — `.slatl` extension formalization.** 2-3h.

Deliverables:
  - Reader convention: `.slat` accepts one-or-many records (many is
    unconventional but legal); `.slatl` expects many records
    line-delimited
  - Writer convention: `.slat` writes a single record with pretty
    indentation; `.slatl` writes one record per line-block, blank-line
    separated
  - Documentation update to Book of SLAT chapter 6 (Two file framings)
    to reflect Alfred's 2026-07-14 lock

Acceptance:
  - `slat-read` / `slat-write` on both extensions round-trip byte-
    identical for the ~1,340 chapters + `books.dewey.slatl`

**Phase D — HTML renderer extends via Rosetta.** 8-12h.

  (Builds on Phase 0 of the 2026-07-13 render-strategy proposal —
   render-book.mjs. If Phase 0 shipped, this is a refactor to route
   through Rosetta instead of hardcoded emitters.)

Deliverables:
  - `render-book.mjs` refactored: SLAT record walk → Rosetta 'html
    lookup → emit
  - Default Rosetta 'html rules cover all canonical kinds
  - Unknown-kind fallback per Section 2 rule (`<div
    class=\"unknown-{kind}\">`)
  - HelloSurface-mini embed placeholder emission (real embed wires in
    Phase E)

Acceptance:
  - Book of SLAT chapters 0-4 render byte-identically before/after
    the Rosetta refactor (proves refactor was pure)
  - Adding a custom kind + a Rosetta rule for it changes output
    without touching the renderer

**Phase E — HelloSurface-mini + hydration + Sakura chat corner.** 20-30h.

  (This is Part Two's original 20-30h, unchanged. Rosetta doesn't add
   or remove work here — it just gives the renderer a clean way to
   emit the embed placeholders.)

Deliverables:
  - `~/code/scheme-lang/embed/hello-surface-mini.js` — L0+L1 bundle,
    no shop/auth
  - `~/code/scheme-lang/embed/sakura-chat-widget.js` — chat corner
  - `~/code/scheme-lang/docs/site/hydrate.mjs` — JS hydration for
    Run/Install/Chat/Animation hooks
  - Animation-hook runtime: verbs bind `target` DOM element, mutate
    per the program

Acceptance:
  - Kid opens Book of Animation ch 5, sees a bouncing dot, changes a
    number, sees it move
  - Chat widget answers 'what does dot mean?' with context of ch 5
  - Animation hook on the chapter title runs on page load

**Phase F — Kid-shares-game URL scheme.** 6-10h.

  (New in Part Two, formalized here.)

Deliverables:
  - Share button in HelloSurface embed controls
  - URL-fragment encoder/decoder (LZ-string or equivalent)
  - Game-load path: URL fragment → HelloSurface program override →
    boot with shared state
  - QR-code generator for the share URL

Acceptance:
  - Kid A builds a game, clicks Share, gets URL
  - Kid B opens URL on a different device, plays same game with same
    initial state

**Phase G — Documentation books.** 6-10h.

Deliverables:
  - `~/code/curator/scheme-books/book-of-rosetta/` — new book:
    what Rosetta is, how rules work, how to fork, tags-are-free
  - `~/code/curator/scheme-books/book-of-dewey/` — new book: what
    Dewey is, how Sakura reads it, how to write a good
    `:sakura-note`
  - Both auto-get MANIFEST + Dewey entries via Phase B tooling

Acceptance:
  - Both books render via Phase D pipeline
  - Book of Rosetta ch 3 walks a real fork example that runs

**What ships in v0.0 vs v0.1.**

  v0.0 (ships at end of Phases A-E):
    - Rosetta with default rules for `'html`, `'training`, `'terminal`,
      `'search`, `'llm-chunk`
    - `books.dewey.slatl` auto-populated for all 31 books, softer
      fields TBD
    - `.slatl` extension formalized and readers/writers updated
    - HTML renderer routed through Rosetta
    - HelloSurface-mini + chat widget wired
    - URL-fragment share for games IS NOT in v0.0 (Phase F)

  v0.1 (adds Phases F + G):
    - Kid-shares-game URL scheme
    - Book of Rosetta + Book of Dewey shipped
    - Softer Dewey fields (`:audience-hint`, `:reach-for-when`,
      `:sakura-note`) hand-filled by Alfred/Sakura over first month
      of use

**Phase gates.**

  - Phase A must ship before D (renderer needs Rosetta)
  - Phase B must ship before Sakura runtime tries `(dewey/*)` verbs
  - Phase C must ship before D (renderer needs the extension
    distinction settled)
  - Phase D must ship before E (embeds need a static-HTML host)
  - Phase E must ship before F (share needs an embed to share from)
  - Phase G can run in parallel with any of the above once Phase A
    lands (writing the books doesn't gate on shipping the runtime)

**Total (Parts Two + Three combined).**

  - Rosetta (A):        6-10h
  - Dewey (B):          3-5h
  - Slatl ext (C):      2-3h
  - Renderer (D):       8-12h
  - HelloSurface (E):  20-30h
  - Share URL (F):      6-10h
  - Docs books (G):     6-10h
  - **TOTAL:          51-80h**

The 51-80h range spans everything Parts Two + Three ask for. Phase A
alone unlocks Rosetta; Phase B alone unlocks Sakura's card catalog;
they can ship independently as milestones the operator can see.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 8 — Open questions for Alfred
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     8
  :title "Open questions for Alfred (decisions before Phases A-G fire)"
  :prose
"None are blockers for the shape — but each, unanswered, becomes a small
tax multiplied across 31 books and however many kinds we grow to.

**Q1. Rosetta default rules file — one big file or split by target?**
Proposal ships `~/code/scheme-lang/rosetta/default.slat` as one file
containing rules for all five targets. Alternative: split into
`rosetta/default-html.slat`, `default-training.slat`, etc., so a
reader can grep per-target. RECOMMENDATION: one file (single source of
truth, easier to reason about default coverage). Grow to split if the
file exceeds ~500 lines. **Alfred picks.**

**Q2. Rosetta rule dispatch — table lookup or predicate function?**
Proposal is table-lookup by `:kind` (fast, deterministic). Alternative:
each rule carries a predicate matching a broader shape of the record
(more expressive, slower, and admits ambiguity we then need conflict-
detection for). RECOMMENDATION: table-lookup by `:kind`, with
`(function <name>)` as the escape hatch for a rule that needs to
inspect other fields. **Alfred confirms.**

**Q3. Dewey read pattern — boot-load everything or lazy per-request?**
Proposal recommends BOTH: boot-load once into memory (~12 KB, cheap),
re-stat on demand to catch mid-session updates. Alternative: lazy read
per-request every time (simple, slower, no in-memory model). RECOMMENDATION:
boot-load + stat-based invalidate. **Alfred confirms; this affects
Sakura's runtime memory footprint by ~12 KB.**

**Q4. Custom-kind namespace — `:custom/*` or `:x/*` (à la HTTP
extension headers)?** Proposal uses `:custom/*`. Shorter alternatives:
`:x/*`, `:_/*`, `:c/*`. RECOMMENDATION: `:custom/*` — self-documenting,
no clash with SLAT's reserved `:_` namespace. **Alfred picks
namespace prefix.**

**Q5. `.slatl` line-delimited definition — literally one line per
record, or blank-line-separated blocks (allowing multi-line records)?**
Multi-line records are the common case (a `(dewey ...)` with 8 keyed
fields wants to span 15 lines). Strict one-per-physical-line is
easier to parse but forces authors to escape newlines in strings.
RECOMMENDATION: blank-line-separated blocks, each block is one record.
The 'l' still means 'line-oriented' at the RECORD level, not the file-
character level. **Alfred confirms.**

**Q6. Kid-shares-game URL host — sakuralabs.dev or a shorter alias?**
Proposal uses `sakuralabs.dev/g/...`. A short-code service would let
Kids type or QR-scan shorter URLs but adds infrastructure. RECOMMENDATION:
full URL for v0.1 launch; short-code service is a Phase F+1 nice-to-
have. **Alfred confirms domain path.**

**Q7. HelloSurface embed weights — bundled per page or hosted?**
Alfred's Part Two note mentions 'weights either bundled or hosted per
page's manifest hint.' Bundled means every book page is self-contained
(works offline, larger initial download); hosted means smaller download
but requires network. RECOMMENDATION: hosted by default with a per-page
`:embed-mode :bundled` opt-in for the hero-game pages the kid shares
with friends (share links need to work anywhere). **Alfred picks
default.**

**Q8. Rosetta fork-authority policy — enforced silence or advertised
openness?** Alfred: 'if they fork it I don't care.' Question: do we
document a fork protocol (e.g. how to publish a bundle so other users
can install it) or leave it silent so the ecosystem doesn't ossify into
a package-manager problem? RECOMMENDATION: silent — a paragraph in
Book of Rosetta says 'the file is Scheme, fork it, share it, we
don't operate a registry.' No package.json equivalent. **Alfred sets
the tone.**

**Q9. Dewey `:sakura-note` write authority — Sakura writes it directly,
or Alfred approves each edit?** Proposal marks Dewey read-only for
Sakura at runtime; the `:sakura-note` field is meant to grow as she
uses the book with humans. Question: does Sakura self-edit the file
(with an audit log), or does she surface proposed edits for Alfred to
review? RECOMMENDATION: propose-then-approve for the first 3 months;
after Alfred's confidence is high, elevate to direct-write with a
diff-log Alfred can review weekly. **Alfred sets the trust ramp.**

**Q10. Cross-cut with prior proposal — `:content-hash` vs `:body-hash`
naming.** The 2026-07-13 proposal Section 9 Q7-analog raised this;
Alfred hasn't confirmed. For consistency with SLAT's canonical
content-addressing (Chapter 9 of Book of SLAT), the field on sibling
records that hashes the fence body should be `:body-hash` to make
clear it hashes ONLY `:body` (not the whole record). RECOMMENDATION:
`:body-hash`. **Alfred confirms; this stabilizes Phase 2 code
extraction across both proposals.**

---

*Questions Q11-Q14 surfaced by Alfred's 2026-07-14 addition (Section 1.5,
filename-as-type + explicit chain).*

**Q11. Compound source types — do we allow them?** Example:
`foo.cart.book.slat` (a cart embedded in a book, or a book that is
also a cart). The typed-filename rule as stated assumes a single type
segment. Compounds would need an ordering convention (outermost-first?
transformation-order?) and Rosetta would need chain rules. RECOMMENDATION:
NO for v0.0 — a file is one type; embedding a cart inside a book is
done via `(cart-embed ...)` records (already in Section 4's palette),
not via filename. Revisit if a real use case shows up. **Alfred picks.**

**Q12. Legacy `.slat` files without type segment — grandfather or
migrate?** Existing curator files like `scheme-books/book-of-*/
NN-title.slat` predate the typed-filename rule. Option A: grandfather
via a compat mode that infers `:book` from parent directory pattern.
Option B: mass-rename all of them to `NN-title.book.slat` in one
commit (git tracks as rename, no content change). RECOMMENDATION:
MIGRATE — Option B. A grandfather path is a permanent tax on every
future reader and every future load-error message. One commit
(`git mv scheme-books/book-of-*/NN-*.slat` → `NN-*.book.slat`)
resolves it forever. **Alfred confirms; this is a Phase 0 addition
to the Book Fix-It burndown.**

**Q13. CLI verb — `rosetta --to <target>` or `cast <source> --to
<target>`?** The reader-behavior spec in Section 1.5 uses `sakura-scheme
rosetta --to <target> <source>`. Alternative shorter form:
`sakura-scheme cast <source> --to <target>`. 'Cast' matches the mental
model (casting a type into another type) and is one syllable. 'Rosetta'
is discoverable (matches the library name) but longer. RECOMMENDATION:
ship BOTH as aliases — `rosetta` as the discoverable long form,
`cast` as the ergonomic short form. `sakura-scheme cast foo.book.slat
--to training` should work. **Alfred picks primary name for help
text.**

**Q14. Dynamic type registry — Scheme file that computes types, or
strictly static list?** A dynamic registry would let a bundle declare
its types programmatically (e.g. `(rosetta-types-from-directory
\"./types/\")`). A static list is one flat block per config file.
RECOMMENDATION: STRICTLY STATIC in v0.0 — every type must appear as a
literal keyword in a `(rosetta-types ...)` block. Reasons: clarity
(a reader can find every type by grep), tooling (an editor can offer
completion), error messages (name the type + the file that declared
it). Dynamic declaration is deferrable to v0.1+ if a real need
appears. **Alfred confirms static.**")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 9 — What already exists we can extend
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     9
  :title "What already exists we can extend — honest enumeration"
  :prose
"Nothing here should be rewritten. Every module below has proven itself
and every extension has a clean seam.

**`~/code/scheme-lang/docs/site/render-ref.mjs`** — the working
reference renderer. 336 lines. Ships a Scheme highlighter (mirrors
`src/repl/highlight.js`), a limited-MD-subset renderer (`renderDocBody`),
`renderCodeBlock` with Run buttons, `renderInline` for inline MD,
`slugify` + heading-anchor generation, sidebar TOC construction. Every
one of those is reusable by `render-book.mjs`. Phase D extracts these
into `render-shared.mjs` (per the 2026-07-13 proposal Section 8) and
the book renderer imports them.

**`~/code/scheme-lang/src/reference-loader.js`** — the reference SLAT
loader (produces `ref.verbList` / `ref.coreList` from
`SAKURA-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat`). The SLAT reader inside it is the
substrate for both loaders. Add a peer `book-loader.js` that produces
`book.chapters` from a book directory; both go through the same SLAT
reader.

**`~/code/scheme-lang/docs/SAKURA-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat`** — the 3.36
MB consolidated reference (1,157 verbs + 70 core forms). Load path
proven. Rosetta v0.0 uses the same loading path for `default.slat`.

**Curator's HelloSurface** (`curator-web/src/scheme/carts/*.sks` + the
runtime in `curator-web/src/scheme/`) — the full HelloSurface app that
Part Two proposes to trim into `hello-surface-mini.js`. Trim = keep L0
(reader, interpreter, macros) + L1 (framebuffer, sound, animation),
drop the shop/auth/cart-commerce paths. Estimated 30-40% of the source
by line count survives. The trim is mechanical.

**Curator's existing `.slat` files** (`~/code/curator/scheme-books/**`)
— the ~1,340 chapter files in the multi-line SLAT format Part One
converted them to. All carry `:prose` with round-trip-safe MD; all
carry `:sha256` provenance; all are already parse-able by the SLAT
reader. Zero re-conversion needed.

**Curator's MANIFEST auto-populator** (from Part One's Phase 1 — 29
book dirs waiting for their MANIFEST.slat). Phase B (Dewey auto-
populator) shares infrastructure — it walks the same book dirs, reads
the same chapter files, emits a companion `books.dewey.slatl` entry
per book. Combined pass = one script that does both.

**Curator's build-cart-index script** (`scripts/build_cart_index.mjs`)
— the shape of a codebase-touching tooling script that stays
deterministic and re-runnable. Phase B's `build-dewey.mjs` follows
the same pattern (idempotent, deterministic, safe to run any time,
runs in pre-commit hook).

**Curator's L-tier model** (L0 / L1 / L2 per Curator's CLAUDE.md) —
already governs where compute happens. HelloSurface-mini's `:scope
(:L0 :L1)` field maps directly to it. No new tier model.

**Curator's vendor-strip rule** (Curator CLAUDE.md 2026-06-22 lock) —
already forbids vendor names in operator-visible copy. Section 6's
`:model \"hosted-mini\"` respects this — capability-tier language, no
vendor identifier. Rosetta's default rules must not emit vendor names
either; Alfred's authored `:sakura-note` in Dewey shouldn't either
(soft convention, not enforced).

**Curator's 3-viewport ship-lock is not this repo** (that's Lacuna
Labs). But its spirit — 'lock in mobile, iPad, desktop on every
change' — applies to Phase E's HelloSurface embeds. The three embed
sizes (96, 256, 1024) are chosen with that shape in mind: the 96
works on any device, the 256 fits comfortably on iPad and desktop,
the 1024 is desktop-first with a graceful mobile responsive fallback
that scales to the viewport.

**Prior Lacuna Eng proposal**
(`~/code/lacuna-labs/research/slat-render-strategy-2026-07-13.slat`)
— 855 lines, 43 KB, nine sections. This proposal EXTENDS it. Every
kind introduced there (`chapter`, `section`, `sakura-says`, `example`,
`cart-embed`, `figure`, `cross-ref`, `warning`, `quote`, `aside`,
`code`, `repl-transcript`, `output`) becomes a canonical entry in
Section 4's palette here. Every emitter target introduced there
(`terminal`, `IDE`, `web`, `search`, `LLM-ingest`) becomes a
Rosetta target here. The style-kit design in that proposal Section 6
composes cleanly with Rosetta — a kit provides visual attributes per
`:kind`, Rosetta provides the emission logic; both merge in the
renderer. Nothing contradicts; this proposal fills in the glue.")


